@flexiarg math-strategy/existence-result
@title Existence-Result Family
@sigils [✶/有]
@keywords existence, exhibit, construction, realisation, demonstration, witness, family-parent
@audience mathematicians, paper-writers, pattern-classifiers
@tone classification / heuristic
@factor Generosity (dāna)
@references [math-informal/construct-an-explicit-witness math-informal/construct-auxiliary-object math-informal/use-probabilistic-method math-informal/numerical-scout]

! conclusion:
  Your paper shows that an object of a desired class exists.

  + context: A class of objects has been defined or implied; whether the class
    is non-empty (or contains an instance with specified properties) is the
    salient question of the paper.

  + IF:
      The paper's main contribution can be expressed as "we show there is an
      X satisfying Y", or "we construct an X satisfying Y", or "for every
      precondition P there is an X with property Q".

  + HOWEVER:
      "Existence" admits many depths: pure-classical (object exists by an
      abstract argument), constructive (an explicit witness is exhibited),
      with-error-bounds (a witness is exhibited with quantitative tolerance),
      via-cross-domain-bridge (existence transferred from a different domain).
      The depth determines downstream usefulness — a theorem prover wants a
      constructive witness, an applied mathematician may need error bounds, a
      structuralist may accept abstract existence. Pick the leaf that matches
      the depth your paper actually reaches.

  + THEN:
      1. Identify the depth: pure-classical / constructive / with-error-bounds /
         via-bridge.
      2. Locate the leaf member-pattern that matches the depth.
      3. Identify the witness that the paper exhibits (or argues exists).
      4. State explicitly what the witness shows and which preconditions
         determine it.

  + BECAUSE:
      Existence claims are the load-bearing skeleton of much of mathematical
      research, but they vary enormously in their constructive content. Putting
      the family parent above its members lets pattern-classification (manual
      or automated) recognise an existence-paper at family granularity even
      when the leaf depth is uncertain, then refine to the leaf when more
      detail is available. The family is the *useful coarse classifier*; the
      leaf is the *precise depth*.

  + MEMBER-PATTERNS:
      member[math-informal/construct-an-explicit-witness]      # constructive
      member[math-informal/construct-auxiliary-object]         # constructive (indirect)
      member[math-informal/use-probabilistic-method]           # pure-classical / non-constructive
      member[math-informal/numerical-scout]                    # with-error-bounds (hint of construction)

  + EXEMPLAR-PAPERS:
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.21888v1]   # Kneser graph Hamilton cycle exists
      exemplar[arxiv-math/0603597v1] # Gevrey ultardistribution algebras (constructive)
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20840v1]   # Z/2-harmonic forms via 4-polytopes (constructive)

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Determine the existence depth and pick the matching leaf.]
      next[Identify the witness explicitly (object + precondition for it).]
      next[Cross-check: does the paper *exhibit* the witness, or only *argue* one exists?]
